{
  "text": "In conclusion, IL-6 is indeed a \"double-edged sword\" [CITATION_1] . Chronic exposure and the concomitant action of pro-inflammatory cytokines such as TNF-\u03b1 cause IL-6 to exhibit pro-inflammatory properties, ultimately leading to muscle catabolism and disruption of immune homeostasis. However, in the absence of proinflammatory cytokines, pulsatile IL-6 release in response to exercise is crucial for myogenesis and the regulation of the inflammatory response. In the context of sarcopenia, we propose that IL-6 signalling may shift towards the pro-inflammatory profile as skeletal muscle function is gradually lost in an aging system ( Fig. 2 ) . IL-7 IL-7 signalling plays an important role in the development and maintenance of immature lymphocytes while also supporting thymic function [CITATION_2] . IL-7 is primarily produced by the stromal and epithelial cells of the thymus [CITATION_3] . The expression of IL-7 declines with age in mice [CITATION_4] . Accordingly, an age dependent decrease of IL-7 serum levels has been reported in humans [CITATION_5] . Recently, IL-7 has been classified as a myokine due to its expression and secretion from skeletal muscle cells [CITATION_6] . While the impact of age on skeletal muscle as a source of IL-7 remains to be investigated, exercise can restore the decline of IL-7 levels observed in old age, highlighting skeletal muscle as a potential source of IL-7 [CITATION_7] . However, down-stream signalling of the IL-7 receptor mediated by Jak1 and \u22123 activation resulting in phosphorylation of STAT-molecules is impaired with age [CITATION_8] . In line with this data, IL7 receptor knock-out mice display defects of early lymphopoiesis characteristic for immune senescence [CITATION_9] . Thus, defective IL-7 signalling is implicated as a link between skeletal muscle and the aging phenotype of immune senescence [CITATION_10] .",
